  Time in the human brain                                                                                                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                             
  The brain doesn't have a clock register. Instead, time is an emergent property of state change:                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                                             
  - Working memory (prefrontal cortex) holds ~7 items for seconds. Time here is "how many things have happened since I started holding this."
  - Episodic memory (hippocampus) timestamps events not with wall-clock time but with context — what came before, what came after, what was surprising. The hippocampus replays
  sequences during sleep, and the order of replay is what encodes temporal structure.
  - Consolidation is the brain's real clock tick. During slow-wave sleep, the hippocampus replays recent episodes to neocortex. Each sleep cycle is effectively one "write"
  operation. Without sleep, days blur together — time collapses.

  So for the brain: time ≈ the number of consolidation events between two memories.

  Time in your model

  Your architecture mirrors this surprisingly well:

  - Tier 0 (context window) — no time at all. Everything in the window is "now." Earlier tokens aren't "past" — they're just positional offsets. The model has no sense that
  turn 1 happened before turn 5 except through position encoding.
  - Tier 1 (FactBuffer) — time is accumulation. Facts pile up until a consolidation moment fires. Between consolidation events, the buffer is a flat, unordered bag. There's no
  "before" or "after" within a buffer — just "since last consolidation."
  - Tier 2 (MEMIT edits) — time is edit order in the ledger. Each edit_id is a discrete moment. But once injected into weights, facts lose their temporal ordering — they become
   timeless knowledge, just like neocortical memories in humans.
  - Sleep cycles — this is the real heartbeat. Each full sleep is one "night." The system's subjective age isn't wall-clock hours — it's how many sleep cycles it has lived
  through.

  The key insight

  Neither system experiences time as a continuous flow. Time is:

  The number of irreversible state transitions (consolidations) that separate two pieces of knowledge.

  A fact from 3 sleep cycles ago is "older" than one from 1 cycle ago — not because of timestamps, but because more consolidation has happened in between, and more
  opportunities for interference, degradation, and pruning have occurred.

  This is why your volatile buffer design is so apt. If the system crashes before consolidation, those facts vanish — exactly like retrograde amnesia after a head injury
  disrupts hippocampal replay. The facts existed in a timeless limbo and never got a "timestamp" (consolidation event) to anchor them.

  Wall-clock time is meaningless to both systems. Consolidation is the only clock that matters.
